1
00:00:00,402 --> 00:00:17,719
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:18,457 --> 00:00:30,952
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodassam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,134 --> 00:00:37,759
So I've chosen this topic of love and relationship.

4
00:00:37,779 --> 00:00:47,469
Well, as you know, huge amounts of literature are written on love from philosophers, psychotherapists, self-helpers,

5
00:00:49,204 --> 00:00:50,106
All religions.

6
00:00:51,268 --> 00:01:00,040
So I don't think I'll be covering everything, but I just want to mention one of, you know, a few of the essentials, really.

7
00:01:01,804 --> 00:01:03,246
So this is just love in general.

8
00:01:03,286 --> 00:01:04,246
It's not specific.

9
00:01:04,307 --> 00:01:10,115
I'm not going to talk about parental love or falling in love, all that sort of stuff.

10
00:01:13,909 --> 00:01:20,659
So I think the first thing that always I find important is just this sense of care.

11
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:25,486
You know, love is a little bit abused, the word love itself.

12
00:01:26,847 --> 00:01:30,272
But it's just understanding that interconnectedness we have.

13
00:01:30,754 --> 00:01:37,784
And it's funny that, you know, with COVID and all that, a lot of people rediscovered neighborliness.

14
00:01:38,784 --> 00:01:42,329
And I think this is really part of this journey.

15
00:01:42,596 --> 00:01:56,234
neoliberal thing you know the most people think of neoliberalism as a operating system an economic operating system based on the market but actually it's an ideology you know

16
00:01:57,007 --> 00:02:05,677
It's on the understanding that everything moves if everybody can just be an entrepreneurial individual.

17
00:02:06,296 --> 00:02:12,544
And what it does is it excites my greed to get things and have experience to get lots of money.

18
00:02:12,604 --> 00:02:17,168
And by doing that, of course, I see you as a competitor.

19
00:02:17,649 --> 00:02:20,110
So this is the system we're in.

20
00:02:20,211 --> 00:02:21,953
We're in a system that...

21
00:02:22,033 --> 00:02:26,683
supports greed and competitiveness.

22
00:02:26,984 --> 00:02:32,034
It's not about coordination, it's not about interconnectedness.

23
00:02:32,316 --> 00:02:36,364
And I think this manifests clearly now with this COVID.

24
00:02:36,731 --> 00:02:44,783
Because, you know, the rich countries, just like individuals, are just looking after themselves and to hell with everybody else.

25
00:02:45,243 --> 00:02:49,531
But unfortunately, the interconnectedness is biting back.

26
00:02:49,550 --> 00:02:56,841
And I'm hoping that it has some effect on the actual system that we're under at the moment.

27
00:02:56,860 --> 00:03:00,646
But just that sense of caring for somebody, you know.

28
00:03:01,876 --> 00:03:17,858
I'm not talking about people who are sick or need help, but just a general attitude of looking after people, being aware of their needs, no matter what it is, caring for them.

29
00:03:17,918 --> 00:03:24,387
I think that's a really sort of important part of that whole syndrome that we call love.

30
00:03:26,409 --> 00:03:30,515
And if we don't do that, if we don't have that sort of attitude, then...

31
00:03:30,832 --> 00:03:36,240
I think we can shade off into controlling people, using them, you know.

32
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:43,889
I mean, abuse is at the far end, but you can also just use people, you know, just for your own benefit.

33
00:03:46,832 --> 00:03:51,199
Sort of a presumption that they will help you, but you don't have to help them.

34
00:03:53,943 --> 00:03:58,207
But I think that sort of really...

35
00:03:58,575 --> 00:04:03,700
undermines a relationship when a person finds that they've been used.

36
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:13,411
I think the other thing is a sort of kindness expressed through a certain affection.

37
00:04:15,272 --> 00:04:23,721
You know, we manifest that with hugging and holding hands and hand on heart, you know, tone of voice, all that sort of stuff.

38
00:04:24,762 --> 00:04:27,704
I mean, the danger is it sort of becomes a...

39
00:04:28,141 --> 00:04:32,425
a bit mawkish, a bit sentimental, you know, huggy-wuggy, touchy-feely stuff.

40
00:04:34,369 --> 00:04:38,574
But I think it's important that there's a sort of expression of affection.

41
00:04:40,055 --> 00:04:55,394
And I don't know about you, but, you know, when I remember acts of unkindness that I've committed, there's always a sort of bitter sorrow that goes with it, you know.

42
00:04:55,696 --> 00:04:57,658
How could I have behaved like that?

43
00:04:57,942 --> 00:05:03,848
And all that really just depends on this sense of being kind.

44
00:05:04,288 --> 00:05:06,011
It's a lovely word, kind.

45
00:05:08,454 --> 00:05:20,607
And when we put these two together and we wonder about how to live with other people, sharing spaces, whether it's intimate or just in an office, doesn't really matter.

46
00:05:21,649 --> 00:05:25,552
And there's this occasion in the scriptures where

47
00:05:25,718 --> 00:05:28,862
the Buddha comes across three Arahats living together.

48
00:05:30,124 --> 00:05:32,266
I think their name, I was trying to find it.

49
00:05:32,326 --> 00:05:34,170
I just couldn't find the passage.

50
00:05:34,189 --> 00:05:38,636
But I think they're called the Anurudas after the chief monk who was with them.

51
00:05:39,216 --> 00:05:42,680
And he asked them, how did they live so peacefully together?

52
00:05:42,701 --> 00:05:51,252
And he says, well, when I get up in the morning, I say to myself, what if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

53
00:05:52,398 --> 00:05:56,324
And of course, if everybody says that, then you have this wonderful harmony.

54
00:05:56,923 --> 00:05:59,908
But if you're the only one who's saying it, then you'll probably get used.

55
00:06:01,992 --> 00:06:20,278
So it's a case of, you know, if you're with somebody, it doesn't matter where it is, as I say, the office or an intimate, just to get that feeling in the group that you're prepared to put aside what you want to do for what somebody else wants to do if it's more beneficial, right?

56
00:06:22,098 --> 00:06:28,586
I mean, it could even happen sort of on holiday, you know, where you've decided to go here and somebody else has decided to go there.

57
00:06:29,127 --> 00:06:32,012
And there's a big rumpus over which one to do.

58
00:06:32,271 --> 00:06:39,362
You know, that doesn't necessarily have to happen if people have the attitude of putting aside what they want.

59
00:06:39,382 --> 00:06:42,466
In other words, you know, not being attached to what one wants to do.

60
00:06:42,947 --> 00:06:44,088
It's a lovely attitude.

61
00:06:45,891 --> 00:06:55,480
But I think underpinning all relationship, actually, are these two qualities of gratitude and forgiveness.

62
00:06:57,146 --> 00:07:12,362
I mean, if we develop this constant sense of gratitude, of being in debt, of wanting to manifest how much we appreciate what's been given to us.

63
00:07:13,084 --> 00:07:23,475
I mean, there's always that desire to help, to communicate, to be with somebody in that sort of grateful way.

64
00:07:24,399 --> 00:07:30,632
And you can't have a relationship which at some point isn't going to hurt.

65
00:07:30,952 --> 00:07:34,901
They're going to say something or do something which is going to upset you.

66
00:07:35,482 --> 00:07:40,872
And if you can't let go of that, if that sort of grudge stays within us, a sense of resentment,

67
00:07:41,257 --> 00:07:44,622
And that really undermines the relationship.

68
00:07:44,682 --> 00:07:50,086
It comes out just in the way we speak and in how we ask them to do things.

69
00:07:50,107 --> 00:07:54,312
It's sort of, it's there within our communication.

70
00:07:56,473 --> 00:07:57,855
And I think that's really important.

71
00:07:58,016 --> 00:08:08,286
And I would have thought that most relationships begin to collapse when one or the other side, you know, just holds onto these grudges, these resentments.

72
00:08:08,307 --> 00:08:11,129
I remember somebody telling me who was a,

73
00:08:12,410 --> 00:08:15,254
a lawyer for family cases.

74
00:08:16,136 --> 00:08:19,302
And there was a divorce.

75
00:08:19,362 --> 00:08:20,384
It was quite bitter.

76
00:08:21,165 --> 00:08:27,194
And he kept saying to the husband, there's no point in going to court for this because you will lose.

77
00:08:28,086 --> 00:08:37,081
It'll be a complete waste of time for you to go to court and get all this out in court because you will lose the case, you know.

78
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:41,788
So he tried to get it across them, but he wanted to go to court.

79
00:08:41,807 --> 00:08:47,076
He wanted somewhere where he could, you know, explain all over the place.

80
00:08:47,856 --> 00:08:53,384
And that's the sort of anger and the bitterness that can come with holding on to resentments.

81
00:08:57,230 --> 00:09:02,937
Just, you know, there's a lovely, I read something quite lovely about this journalist.

82
00:09:03,318 --> 00:09:05,380
She'd gone down in America.

83
00:09:05,461 --> 00:09:08,525
She'd gone down to see how dolphins are trained.

84
00:09:09,567 --> 00:09:22,225
And what she saw was that whenever a dolphin didn't jump through the hoop or play the trick or fail to do the trick, nothing was said, absolutely nothing.

85
00:09:22,288 --> 00:09:29,378
And then they sort of did the usual routine and the dolphin would complete the trick.

86
00:09:29,778 --> 00:09:37,688
When the dolphin completes the trick, the trainers jumped up and down with great joy, shouting and whooping and making all sorts of great noises.

87
00:09:39,270 --> 00:09:44,217
So she thought, well, I wonder if this would work on my husband.

88
00:09:44,238 --> 00:09:48,283
So when she went back home, she never criticized him.

89
00:09:48,302 --> 00:09:49,424
She never said anything.

90
00:09:49,485 --> 00:09:51,908
But every time he did something that,

91
00:09:52,192 --> 00:09:59,658
pleased her or he did something the way she wanted him to do, she would jump up and down with great joy and blow trumpets.

92
00:10:01,259 --> 00:10:06,264
And he changed completely without knowing it, you know, it was very harmonious.

93
00:10:06,946 --> 00:10:10,668
And then of course he went and told her, she went and told him.

94
00:10:11,269 --> 00:10:20,038
And so he found that also worked, even if it's a consciousness, even if it's a conscious thing that the other person knows what you're doing.

95
00:10:20,018 --> 00:10:22,160
It actually works.

96
00:10:22,481 --> 00:10:37,125
So holding back on criticisms and all that sort of stuff and really rejoicing when the person does something which is to your benefit seems to be the trick, really, of getting people to do what you want them to do.

97
00:10:41,211 --> 00:10:47,562
And the final thing is, of course, our spiritual well-being.

98
00:10:49,582 --> 00:10:56,912
I mean, obviously, if you're living with somebody who's on your path, then that's a tremendous sort of boost, isn't it?

99
00:10:57,511 --> 00:11:03,779
I mean, I've known people who've taken to the Buddhist path, but their partner really just doesn't like it.

100
00:11:03,820 --> 00:11:05,020
The spouse doesn't like it.

101
00:11:05,522 --> 00:11:07,203
And it's been a point of contention.

102
00:11:08,085 --> 00:11:15,232
But if you happen to be living with somebody who's actually practicing with you, it's obviously a massive support, you know.

103
00:11:15,933 --> 00:11:18,476
And it's the same with any friendship that does it.

104
00:11:19,081 --> 00:11:23,166
And just to sort of end with this lovely quote from the Buddha.

105
00:11:23,846 --> 00:11:30,956
So he's Ananda, who was with him for the last 20 years of his life as a personal assistant.

106
00:11:32,498 --> 00:11:35,562
He always thinks he knows a bit more than he actually does.

107
00:11:36,442 --> 00:11:47,738
And on this occasion, he said to the Buddha, Bhagavan, this is half the spiritual life, good friendship, good companionship and good comradeship.

108
00:11:48,577 --> 00:11:51,341
And the Buddha says, oh, not so, Ananda, not so.

109
00:11:51,361 --> 00:11:56,250
This is the entire spiritual life.

110
00:11:56,269 --> 00:12:00,557
That is good friendship, good companionship and good comradeship.

111
00:12:01,317 --> 00:12:11,114
For when someone has a good friend, a good companion and a good comrade, it is to be expected they will develop and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path.

112
00:12:12,336 --> 00:12:16,121
So that was his vision.

113
00:12:16,355 --> 00:12:19,900
understanding of what friendship was, you know, a good friendship.

114
00:12:20,743 --> 00:12:28,196
And of course, if we remember, he was with his five friends when, you know, he left them.

115
00:12:29,037 --> 00:12:30,519
They all thought he'd gone soft.

116
00:12:30,539 --> 00:12:40,658
Remember, he was practicing this ascetic asceticism, which was basically not eating, letting go of the body, you know.

117
00:12:41,177 --> 00:12:46,092
And he was with five friends, five close friends who were all practicing together.

118
00:12:46,433 --> 00:12:55,322
And we all know that, you know, practicing with people in a group is so much more encouraging than doing it by yourself.

119
00:12:55,774 --> 00:13:12,035
So all these points, I mean, there's a lot more, of course, I'm sure that you could think of it, think of them, but just, you know, bringing to mind that sense of care, affection and kindness, especially kindness.

120
00:13:12,116 --> 00:13:12,576
I don't know.

121
00:13:12,596 --> 00:13:20,027
It's a big thing with me that these underlying attitudes of gratitude and forgiveness are

122
00:13:20,951 --> 00:13:34,306
And then finally, just that ability to be with somebody without open to their ideas, to their understandings, even in conversation, even in conversation.

123
00:13:34,326 --> 00:13:42,173
What if I put aside my ideas, you know, my views, my opinions and open up to what the other one has to say?

124
00:13:42,754 --> 00:13:46,317
So often we don't like to do that because they might change our minds.

125
00:13:48,172 --> 00:13:58,931
So it's a case of, you know, looking at our relationships from this point of view of being with another human being who's like us.

126
00:13:59,150 --> 00:14:01,375
So I'm a human being and you're a human being.

127
00:14:01,836 --> 00:14:02,937
And just remembering that.

128
00:14:03,698 --> 00:14:11,513
And that, I think, produces for us that sort of relationship of kindness and care.

129
00:14:13,096 --> 00:14:13,658
Very good.

130
00:14:14,039 --> 00:14:28,437
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and I have not caused any confusion and that you will, by your practice of loving kindness, be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

